org.qteam.tinyicon

Class TinyIcon

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.qteam.tinyicon.TinyIcon

  • public final class TinyIcon
extends java.lang.Object
    The main class to load and convert icons/favicons to BufferedImage or PNG bytes. TinyIcon allows to load and decode .ico files very easily.
    A single icon file usually contains multiple images (e.g. with different resolution or color depth), so several methods are available to get a particular icon or image (See getIcon or getImage methods).
    Additionally icons can also be sorted to get, for example, the smallest available icon (See sortIcons method).

    Basic usage:

    1) Construct a TinyIcon:

    // Local icon
    final TinyIcon ti = new TinyIcon ("c:/icons/myicon.ico");
    or
    // Favicon
    final TinyIcon ti = new TinyIcon ("https://www.github.com");

    2) Get a specific Icon:

    // Get the third Icon (Order depends in how the icons are stored in the .ico file)
    final Icon ico = ti.getIcon (2);
    or
    // Get a specific Icon based on a condition:
    final Icon ico = ti.getIcon (i -> ((i.getWidth () == 48) && (i.getHeight () == 48)));

    3) Work with the Icon:

    // Get the associated BufferedImage
    final BufferedImage img = ico.getImage ();
    or
    // Query some information
    System.out.printf ("img width = %d, img height = %d\n", ico.getWidth (), ico.getHeight ());

    Advanced usage:

    1) Query library information:

    final String bd = TinyIcon.getLibraryBuildDate ();
    System.out.printf ("version = %s, build date = %s, library path = %s\n\n", TinyIcon.getLibraryVersion (), ((bd == null) ? "Unknown" : bd), TinyIcon.getLibraryPath ());

    2) Sort icons:

    final TinyIcon ti = new TinyIcon ("myicon.ico");

    // Sort icons from bigger to smaller (first by resolution, then by bits per pixel)
    ti.sortIcons (IconSort.BY_RESOLUTION_DESCENDING, IconSort.BY_BPP_DESCENDING);

    3) Extract a subset of icons:

    final TinyIcon ti = new TinyIcon ("myicon.ico");

    // Get all icons that have width > 16 and bpp < 32
    final ArrayList <Icon> icons = ti.extractIcons (i -> ((i.getWidth () > 16) && (i.getBpp () < 32)));

    4) Extract a subset of images:

    final TinyIcon ti = new TinyIcon ("myicon.ico");

    // Get all images that have width > 16 and bpp < 32
    final ArrayList <BufferedImage> images = ti.extractImages (i -> ((i.getWidth () > 16) && (i.getBpp () < 32)));

    GitHub page: https://github.com/qteam-github/TinyIcon

    • Constructor Detail

      • TinyIcon

        public TinyIcon(java.lang.String filename_or_url)
         throws java.io.IOException,
                InvalidIconException,
                InvalidIconDataException
        Constructs a new TinyIcon and loads / processes the specified icon file.
        See the basic usage description for some examples.
        Parameters:
        filename_or_url - The local path of the .ico file or a remote address to load favicons. In case of remote addresses is not necessary to specify any icon name; a 'favicon.ico' is automatically appended to the URL. Accepted protocols are: https, http and ftp.
        Throws:
        java.io.IOException - if an I/O exception occurs during loading the .ico file (e.g. a non existent file or URL).
        InvalidIconException - if the file is an invalid icon (e.g. a corrupted file or if you try to load a different file instead of a .ico one).
        InvalidIconDataException - if the icon has wrong data inside (e.g. invalid image header or unsupported bitCount value).

    • Method Detail

      • sortIcons

        public void sortIcons(IconSort sort_type_1,
                      IconSort sort_type_2)
        Sorts all icons using the specified primary and secondary keys.
        This method allows up to two sort keys; first all icons are sorted using the primary key, then the secondary key.
        The icons can be sorted by image resolution, bits per pixel and image compression and both ascending or descending order can be used.

        Valid values for sort_type are:

        • NONE
        • BY_RESOLUTION_ASCENDING
        • BY_RESOLUTION_DESCENDING
        • BY_BPP_ASCENDING
        • BY_BPP_DESCENDING
        • BY_COMPRESSION_ASCENDING
        • BY_COMPRESSION_DESCENDING

        Example:
        To sort icons first by image area (ascending), then by bit per pixel (descending) use: ti.sortIcons (IconSort.BY_RESOLUTION_ASCENDING, IconSort.BY_BPP_DESCENDING);
        where ti is a constructed TinyIcon.

        Note that the sorting only occurs in memory (in an internal ArrayList); the original .ico file is not modified.

        Parameters:
        sort_type_1 - The primary key for sorting.
        sort_type_2 - The secondary key for sorting.

      • getIcon

        public Icon getIcon(int index)
        Returns the Icon at the specified position in the internal icons list.
        Initial order of the icons (unless you sort them) depends in how they are stored in the .ico file (e.g. by an icon editor program).
        Parameters:
        index - Position of the element to return.
        Returns:
        the Icon at the specified position in the list.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is out of range [(index < 0) || (index >= getNumOfIcons ())].

      • getIcon

        public Icon getIcon(java.util.function.Predicate<Icon> condition)
        Returns the first occurence of the Icon that matches the given condition.
        To build conditions, the methods of the class Icon can be used.

        Here are some examples:

        // Get the first icon with width and height > 32
        final Icon ico1 = ti.getIcon (i -> ((i.getWidth () > 32) && (i.getHeight () > 32)));

        // Get the first icon with bpp = 8
        final Icon ico2 = ti.getIcon (i -> (i.getBpp () == 8));

        where ti is a constructed TinyIcon.

        Parameters:
        condition - a Predicate expression to be evaluated.
        Returns:
        the first Icon that matches the specified condition or null if the condition is not satisfied.

      • getImage

        public java.awt.image.BufferedImage getImage(java.util.function.Predicate<Icon> condition)
        Returns the first occurence of the BufferedImage that matches the given condition.
        To build conditions, the methods of the class Icon can be used.

        Here are some examples:

        // Get the first compressed image with height >= 256 and bpp = 32
        final Icon ico1 = ti.getIcon (i -> (i.isPng () && (i.getHeight () >= 256) && (i.getBpp () == 32)));

        // Get the first image with width >= 128 or bpp < 8
        final Icon ico2 = ti.getIcon (i -> (i.getWidth () >= 128) || (i.getBpp () < 8)));

        where ti is a constructed TinyIcon.

        Parameters:
        condition - a Predicate expression to be evaluated.
        Returns:
        the first BufferedImage that matches the specified condition or null if the condition is not satisfied.

      • getImageAsPng

        public byte[] getImageAsPng(int index)
        Returns the image (as png byte array) at the specified position in the internal icons list.
        This method is similar to getImage (int) but the returned BufferedImage is converted to png byte array using the ImageIO.write method.
        Initial order of the images (unless you sort them) depends in how they are stored in the .ico file (e.g. by an icon editor program).
        Parameters:
        index - Position of the element to return.
        Returns:
        the byte array with the png data at the specified position in the list or null if an error occurs.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the index is out of range [(index < 0) || (index >= getNumOfIcons ())].
        See Also:
        getImage (int)

      • getImageAsPng

        public byte[] getImageAsPng(java.util.function.Predicate<Icon> condition)
        Returns the first occurence of the image (as png byte array) that matches the given condition.
        This method is similar to getImage (Predicate <Icon>) but the returned BufferedImage is converted to png byte array using the ImageIO.write method.
        To build conditions, the methods of the class Icon can be used.

        Here are some examples:

        // Get the first image data with height = 512
        final byte ico1 [] = ti.getIcon (i -> (i.getHeight () == 512));

        // Get the first compressed image data with bpp >= 24
        final byte ico2 [] = ti.getIcon (i -> (i.isPng () && (i.getBpp () >= 24)));

        where ti is a constructed TinyIcon.

        Parameters:
        condition - a Predicate expression to be evaluated.
        Returns:
        the first image (as png byte array) that matches the specified condition or null if an error occurs or if the condition is not satisfied.
        See Also:
        getImage (Predicate <Icon>)

      • extractIcons

        public java.util.ArrayList<Icon> extractIcons(java.util.function.Predicate<Icon> condition)
        Extracts all icons that match the given condition.
        When extracting icons, a new ArrayList is created as subset of the original list.
        To build conditions, the methods of the class Icon can be used.

        Here are some examples:

        // Get all icons that have width and height > 32
        final ArrayList <Icon> list1 = ti.extractIcons (i -> ((i.getWidth () > 32) && (i.getHeight () > 32)));

        // Get all icons that have bpp = 8
        final ArrayList <Icon> list2 = ti.extractIcons (i -> (i.getBpp () == 8));

        where ti is a constructed TinyIcon.

        Parameters:
        condition - a Predicate expression to be evaluated.
        Returns:
        a new ArrayList containing all icons that match the specified condition or an empty ArrayList if the condition is not satisfied.

      • extractImagesAsPng

        public java.util.ArrayList<byte[]> extractImagesAsPng(java.util.function.Predicate<Icon> condition)
        Extracts all images (as png byte array) that match the given condition.
        This method is similar to extractImages (Predicate <Icon>) but the returned BufferedImage is converted to png byte array using the ImageIO.write method, however, if an error occurs during png image conversion, the (missing/null) image data is not added to the final ArrayList.

        When extracting images, a new ArrayList is created as subset of the original list.
        To build conditions, the methods of the class Icon can be used.

        Here are some examples:

        // Get all images that have height = 512
        final ArrayList <byte []> list1 = ti.extractImagesAsPng (i -> (i.getHeight () == 512));

        // Get all compressed images that have bpp >= 24
        final ArrayList <byte []> list2 = ti.extractImagesAsPng (i -> (i.isPng () && (i.getBpp () >= 24)));

        where ti is a constructed TinyIcon.

        Parameters:
        condition - a Predicate expression to be evaluated.
        Returns:
        a new ArrayList containing all images (as png byte array) that match the specified condition or an empty ArrayList if the condition is not satisfied.
